{{no footnotes|date=October 2013}} {{Infobox person | name = Michael Yang | image = | caption = | birth_place = | occupation = [[Entrepreneur]] | networth = | spouse = | children = 4 | website = http://www.michaelyang.com/ | footnotes = | module = {{Infobox Korean name|child=yes |hangul = 양민정 |hanja = 梁民正 |mr = Yang Minjǒng |rr = Yang Minjeong}} }} '''Michael Yang''' is a [[Korean American]] technology [[entrepreneur]]. He was born in [[Seoul]], [[South Korea]] and moved to [[San Jose, California|San Jose]], [[California]] on April 2, 1976, with his family when he was 14 years old.{{citation needed|date=October 2013}}
After attending [[UC Berkeley]] and [[Columbia University]] graduate school, Michael worked for [[Xerox]], [[Intergraph]], [[Televideo]], [[Samsung]] and [[Jazz Multimedia]] before starting his first [[venture capital]] backed [[Startup company|startup]] company [[mysimon|mySimon]] with Yeogirl Yun in April 1998.{{citation needed|date=October 2013}} [[mysimon|mySimon]] was acquired by CNET in 2000 for $700 million during the Internet boom.
He then started [[Become.com]] in January 2004 and raised $37 million in capital from TPG, Transcosmos, EFF and Ron Conway.{{citation needed|date=October 2013}}
Michael has served as member of the IT Advisory Council for President [[George W. Bush]] in 2001 and as an advisory board member of Creative Economy Leader advisory group for President [[Park Geun-hye]] of South Korea in 2013.
Michael's story has been written about in publications such as Businessweek, MIT Technology Review, and Christianity Today magazines.{{citation needed|date=October 2013}}
