{{Infobox officeholder |name = Rizalino Navarro |image = |imagesize = |order = 18th |office = Secretary of Trade and Industry (Philippines) |term_start = 1992 |term_end = 1996 |president = [[Fidel Ramos]] |predecessor = Lilia R. Bautista |successor = Cesar B. Bautista |birth_date = December 30, 1938 |birth_place = |death_date = July 7, 2011 (aged 72) |death_place = [[Makati]], [[Philippines]] |party = |spouse = |relations = |children = |alma_mater = [[University of the East]] <sub>([[Bachelor's Degree|B.S.]])</sub>, [[Harvard Business School]] <sub>([[Master of Business Administration|M.B.A]])</sub> |occupation = [[Entrepreneur]] }}
'''Rizalino S. Navarro''' (December 30, 1938 – July 7, 2011) was a [[Philippines|Filipino]] [[businessman]], business executive and [[politician]]. Navarro served as the [[Department of Trade and Industry (Philippines)|Secretary of Trade and Industry]] from 1992 to 1996 within the [[Cabinet (government)|Cabinet]] of former [[Philippines President]] [[Fidel Ramos]].<ref name=abscbn>{{cite news|first=Coco|last=Alcuaz|title=Ex-DTI chief Navarro dies |url=http://www.abs-cbnnews.com/business/07/07/11/ex-dti-chief-navarro-dies |work=[[ABS-CBN News Channel]] |date=2011-07-07|accessdate=2011-07-07}}</ref><ref name=pi>{{cite news|first=Doris C.|last=Dumlao|title=Former trade chief Rizalino Navarro dies of heart attack; 72 |url=http://business.inquirer.net/6207/former-trade-chief-rizalino-navarro-dies-of-heart-attack-72 |work=[[Philippine Daily Inquirer]] |date=2011-07-07|accessdate=2011-07-07}}</ref>
Navarro earned a [[bachelor's degree]] in [[business administration]] [[cum laude]] from [[University of the East]].<ref name=abscbn/> He earned a [[Master of Business Administration]] from [[Harvard Business School]].<ref name=abscbn/>
Navarro also served as the [[chief executive officer]] of both [[Sycip Gorres Velayo & Co.|SGV & Co.]], the largest [[accounting]] [[firm]] in the Philippines, and [[Rizal Commercial Banking Corporation]] (RCBC).<ref name=abscbn/> Navrro launched his career at SGV in 1982 and rose to [[managing director]] of the firm by 1992, when he left to become Secretary of Trade.<ref name=abscbn/>
He became Secretary of Trade through the invitation of then [[Finance Secretary]] [[Ramon del Rosario]], who was one of Navarro's classmates at [[Harvard University]].<ref name=abscbn/>
Rizalino Navarro died of an apparent heart attack at the RCBC corporate [[gym]] in [[Makati City]] on July 7, 2011, at the age of 72.<ref name=abscbn/>
